# {{REPO_NAME}} — harness constitution

This repository is a **harness**, not an application. It builds {{PROJECT_COUNT}} separate projects from the specs in `brief/`, each into its own repo under `{{PROJECTS_DIR}}/` (gitignored here).

{{PURPOSE}}

## The one rule

**No production code without a failing test on record.**

This is enforced mechanically, not by good intentions. A `PreToolUse` hook blocks every write to a project's shipped code — the paths named in `guarded` in `.claude/harness.json` — until `harness.py red` has run a test and watched it fail. Tests, `__init__.py`, config and CI files are never blocked. See [ADR-0003](docs/adr/0003-mechanical-red-gate.md).

If the gate blocks you, you skipped a step. Write the test.
`HARNESS_GATE_BYPASS=1` exists for emergencies and appears in the transcript when used. Using it to save time is the single way to make this harness worthless.

## Startup workflow

Before writing code:

1. Run `./init.sh`. It checks the environment, proves the TDD gate still blocks, and runs every scaffolded project's suite. **If it fails, repair that before adding scope** — a harness on a broken baseline just makes the breakage restartable.
2. Read this file.
3. Read `HANDOFF.md` for the next action, and `PROGRESS.md` for the board.
4. Run `python3 .claude/scripts/harness.py lessons`. It is an index, not the archive — open only the entries whose trigger matches what you are about to do. A lesson nobody reads is a lesson nobody learned.
5. `git log --oneline -5` in the project you're about to touch.

## End of session

1. `python3 .claude/scripts/harness.py status --write`
2. `python3 .claude/scripts/harness.py handoff`
3. Commit. Leave the repo so the next session can run `./init.sh` immediately.

## Definition of done — for a cycle

All five, or it is not done:

- [ ] The behaviour is implemented and the cycle's tests pass
- [ ] The quality gates actually ran ({{QUALITY_GATES}})
- [ ] **Evidence recorded** — what ran, what it printed, the `[RED]` and `[GREEN]` SHAs
- [ ] The repo still starts from `./init.sh`
- [ ] **Anything surprising is written down** — see below. Nothing surprising happened is a fine answer; "no time" is not.

Evidence is the anti-false-done mechanism. `harness.py cycle <project> <id> done` **refuses without it**, because a `done` nobody can check is indistinguishable from a lie. Project-level DoD lives in each brief and in `docs/PLAYBOOK.md`.

## When something surprises you, write it down before moving on

A bug that fooled the tests is worth more than the fix. The fix takes minutes and helps once; the reason it got past the discipline is what stops the next one. **Fixing it and saying nothing is the waste.**

So when any of these happen, the work is not finished until it is recorded:

| What happened | Where it goes |
|---|---|
| A green suite was wrong — the bug was real and the tests still passed | a new `docs/lessons/NNNN-*.md` |
| The tool did the opposite of what its docs led you to expect | a new lesson |
| A stated assumption in a comment or doc turned out false | a new lesson, **and fix the comment** |
| The fix sets a rule for code not written yet | an **ADR** (+ the lesson that forced it) |
| A lesson contradicts an accepted ADR | the lesson **and** supersede that ADR |

The bar and the file shape are in `docs/lessons/0000-how-to-write-one.md`: it must change what someone does next time. Not a diary, not a changelog. Write the **surprise** — what you expected versus what happened — because that is the part that transfers; a lesson that only records the fix is a changelog entry.

An ADR is for a decision that is hard to reverse. A one-line escape fix is not — that is a lesson.

**Retire a lesson the moment it becomes a check.** When a lesson's failure mode is blocked by a gate probe, a test, or a lint rule, set `**Status:** mechanised` and name the check in `**Enforced by:**`. It leaves the index and stops competing for attention, because the check is now the lesson. The prose stays as the reason the check exists.

This is also how the record stays affordable. Lessons and ADRs are read through an index — `harness.py lessons`, `harness.py adrs` — one line each, full text opened only on a match. Nothing here is loaded wholesale, so the cost of the archive is the length of the index, and retirement is what keeps that short.

Two failure modes this exists to prevent:

- **Documentation that lies.** A description of an enforcement mechanism is a claim; when the mechanism changes, the claim is part of the change.
- **A fix that lands without its reason.** If that is not written down, the next agent trusts the suite again.

## Escalation

- **Cycle blocked twice** — the brief is ambiguous, not the agent wrong. Read the brief section, decide, record it (ADR if hard to reverse, `CONTEXT.md` if it's a word), then reset the cycle.
- **A term isn't in `CONTEXT.md`** — add it there before using it in code.
- **Architecture or scope question the brief doesn't answer** — ask the user. Don't invent scope.

## Layout

```
init.sh                     the one verification entrypoint — run it before and after work
brief/                      the specs — the contract, read fully before coding
{{PROJECTS_DIR}}/<name>/    built code; each is its own repo and its own remote
.claude/harness.json        owner, guarded paths, runner definitions — the only project-specific config
.claude/cycles/*.json       the ordered TDD cycles per project, lifted from each brief
.claude/state/*.json        gate state, coverage, cycle progress, evidence (machine-written)
.claude/scripts/harness.py  gate hook, red/green, cycle tracking, token accounting, handoff
docs/adr/                   decisions that were hard to reverse (index: harness.py adrs)
docs/lessons/               what we learned the expensive way (index: harness.py lessons)
CONTEXT.md                  domain glossary — the words the code must use
PROGRESS.md                 generated dashboard; never hand-edit
HANDOFF.md                  generated next-action for the next session; never hand-edit
```

## Commands

| | |
|---|---|
| `./init.sh` | verify environment, gate, and every scaffolded suite |
| `/harness-build <project> [cycle]` | orchestrate the next TDD cycle via subagents |
| `/harness-status` | dashboard: cycles, gate, coverage, per-subagent tokens |
| `harness.py red <project> <test>` | run a test, require failure, open the gate |
| `harness.py green <project>` | run the suite, shut the gate, record coverage |
| `harness.py cycle <p> <id> done --evidence "…"` | close a cycle; refuses without evidence |
| `harness.py handoff` | write `HANDOFF.md` for the next session |
| `harness.py lessons` / `adrs` | the reference index — read before dispatching, open only what applies |

## Stack — fixed by the briefs, not open for improvement

{{STACK}}

## Working agreements

- Cycles run in the order in `.claude/cycles/`. No skipping; later tests depend on earlier code.
- Every cycle lands as two commits: `[RED]` (the failing test) then `[GREEN]` (the code). The git log is the evidence.
- A subagent implements a cycle; a reviewer audits it; the orchestrator marks it done. The implementer is never the judge of its own work.
- Push after every green cycle.
- Terminology comes from `CONTEXT.md`. If you need a word that isn't there, add it there first.
